 To create a big matrix in LaTeX in landscape orientation, you'll need to:

1. Use the `landscape` environment to rotate the page
2. Use appropriate matrix environments for your matrix
3. Consider additional packages for better control of large matrices

Here's how to do it:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{lscape}  % For landscape orientation
\usepackage{amsmath} % For math environments
\usepackage{geometry} % For page layout adjustments

\begin{document}

% Switch to landscape mode
\begin{landscape}
  % You might want to adjust margins for more space
  \setlength{\mathindent}{0pt}

  \begin{equation}
  \begin{bmatrix}
    a_{11} & a_{12} & a_{13} & \ldots & a_{1n} \\
    a_{21} & a_{22} & a_{23} & \ldots & a_{2n} \\
    \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\
    a_{m1} & a_{m2} & a_{m3} & \ldots & a_{mn}
  \end{bmatrix}
  \end{equation}

\end{landscape}

\end{document}
```

For particularly large matrices, you might also consider:

- Using the `adjustbox` package to scale the matrix: `\usepackage{adjustbox}` and then wrap your matrix in `\adjustbox{scale=0.8}{...}`
- Using the `resizebox` command to fit the matrix to page width: `\resizebox{\textwidth}{!}{...}`
- For very large matrices, the `nicematrix` package offers better control with `\begin{pNiceMatrix}...\end{pNiceMatrix}`

